{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2b1ddee9-bcf9-4231-a4d9-ccdb00c4a696","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe report confirms it: the bottleneck isn't compilation — it's **MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server process in memory.\n\n## Recommendations (highest impact first)\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Build Server\nSet this environment variable so MSBuild reuses a persistent server process between CLI builds, just like VS does:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\nAdd it to your shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`, PowerShell `$PROFILE`) for permanent use. This eliminates the ~1.5-2s startup overhead per invocation.\n\n### 2. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\nFor rapid edit-build-test cycles, avoid re-invoking the CLI entirely:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\nThis keeps the process alive, watches for file changes, and triggers fast incremental rebuilds automatically.\n\n### 3. Upgrade to .NET 9+ for Terminal Build Acceleration\nIf upgrading the `TargetFramework` is an option, .NET 9 introduced **Terminal Build Acceleration** — add to the `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TerminalBuildAcceleration>true</TerminalBuildAcceleration>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThis skips redundant up-to-date checks and can reduce no-op builds to near-zero overhead.\n\n### Summary\n\n| Approach | Effort | Impact |\n|---|---|---|\n| `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | Env var | Eliminates startup cost (~2s) |\n| `dotnet watch build` | Workflow change | Near-instant rebuilds |\n| .NET 9 Terminal Build Acceleration | TFM upgrade | Best-in-class CLI perf |\n\nThe MSBuild server env var is the quickest win — no code changes needed, and it directly addresses the startup overhead gap between CLI and Visual Studio.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f294297e-ada5-44f3-8a0b-c1a2dc1df4a1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer report makes it clear: the overhead is from MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation on every CLI invocation. Visual Studio doesn't have this problem because it keeps an MSBuild server process warm.\n\nThe key solution here is the **MSBuild Server** (also known as the MSBuild build server or `dotnet build-server`). Starting with .NET 8 SDK, there's a feature where MSBuild can reuse a long-lived server process to avoid the startup cost. This is controlled by the `DOTNET_CLI_DO_NOT_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable (set to `0` to enable) or the `-nodeReuse:true` flag, but more importantly, the newer approach is:\n\n\nFor the inner development loop, `dotnet watch build` keeps the process alive and rebuilds on file changes, eliminating the startup penalty. The most impactful fix is setting `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` in .NET 8+, which enables the persistent MSBuild server that avoids re-evaluating the project graph between builds. The MSBuild server can be enabled with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` for the biggest performance boost. For development workflows, `dotnet watch build` keeps the process alive and avoids startup overhead entirely. I should also mention configuring the artifacts output layout and considering Visual Studio's build acceleration settings to further optimize incremental builds. I should also consider what project-level configurations might help optimize the build process, and verify whether the dotnet CLI is actually available in this environment so I can provide a working demonstration.","outputTokens":1571},"id":"4c8dcadc-2efa-436c-b71c-13902818c194","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:52:59.372Z","parentId":"2b8b75f5-3365-498b-bad5-addca003cc22"}
